<GUIClass name="CMUI_ComboBox" id="b4cd729e-b6f9-4784-9e8b-74f980e21db8">
    <superclass name="ComboBox"/>
    <transient/>
    <sharedTransientAllowed/>
    <subclassSharedTransientAllowed/>
    <subclassTransientAllowed/>
    <transientAllowed/>
    <text>



TFS 54538 - Filtering

Filter is on for all CMUI_ComboBox and CMUI_FieldComboBoxControl, filter can be turned off individually if necessary.

The filter is achieved by setting the 'itemLevel' for the non matching items to 2. This basically removes them from the combo list, but they are still in the collection on the combo box, so all items can be reshown by setting itemLevel to 1.

Setting the itemLevel is fine BUT the first item in the list (itemObject[1]) must be itemLevel 1. This means that if the first item does not match the filter you have this odd looking list with the first item being incorrectly in the list.

So solution will include a way to identify the first visible item after the filter and then switch that first visible and itemObject[1] so that something that matches the filter is the first in the list. 

After selection of an item, from the filtered list, the list is re displayed (all items set itemLevel to 1) and items that were switched are switched back. This works well; however, combo boxes that are set using the listCollection() method cannot have the switching, it will create a 14072 error. So will need an exception handler for 14072.

This means the listCollection() combo boxes will have an odd first item that might not match the filter, however this is not an issue in combos that have a blank as the first item, it looks ok. But lots of combo boxes do not have a blank because a value must be selected.

The combobox style will also be changed on all CMUI_Comboxes to be Style_DropDown so that text can be entered in a way that supports filtering.

The helpContextId is used to know if the up arrow or down arrow key has been pressed , this allows a filtered list to then have an item selected using arrow keys.

</text>
